      "beat_count": 8,
      "conditioning_notes": "`<CHAR_A>`'s love of holding things together and fear of losing control of the room drive the list-anxiety in the opening — they can see the whole situation from the vantage point but can't stop cataloguing what's wrong. `<CHAR_B>`'s love of taking care of people and fear of not being needed shows up in the repeated food check and in the quiet recognition of `<CHAR_A>`'s discomfort — they are most useful in the unspoken moment, not the crisis. `<CHAR_C>`'s love of rising to the moment and fear of letting the group down surface through action not speech — they ask for the list, take one snack, and go; they deflect no credit because they weren't there for credit. The vantage location archetype shapes the whole sequence: characters speak differently from up high — more plainly, with less performance. The height gives `<CHAR_A>` the perspective they need to teach and the distance they need to eventually let go. The falling arc is not a collapse; it's a controlled release — each beat the grip loosens one notch, until the ending, which earns its stillness."
